RT-PCR positivity duration

Pablo Perez

19/10/2020

In Eurosurveillance 2020 Jul 30; 25(30): 2001292, Omar et al.analysed data of consecutive RT-qPCR results in 537 symptomatic patients with mild COVID-19 in home quarantine, between 28 February to 6 June 2020 in Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany. Table 1 presents their reported data on the population with an RT-qPCR positive for SARS-CoV-2 RNA at mean (95%CI) days after symptom onset. They reported a median time to testing negative of 20 days (IQR 16-28).

Simulated study population

For i in 1:1,000, at each iteration of time t, sample n random numbers \[\ n \ = \space n_{t} \ - \ n_{t-1}\] from a normal distribution with mean = mu and sd = sigma, given upper and lower bounds of observed time.

At each step i, fit a gamma distribution by maximum likelihood, obtain its parameters and then average across all 1,000 iterations.

Fit gamma accelerated failure time regression

Using simulated datasets above, lets fit a gamma accelerated failure time regression model and obtain parameters.

Fit Erlang distribution

From the gamma accelerated failure function fitted to simulated data edata, extract the cumulative distribution function ccdf_pcr parameters over a sequence of survival probability of length 21 (e.g.0, 0.05, 0.10, 0.95, 0.99). That is, the likelihood of remaining positive over normalised observation time. Also extract ovrall mean, median and IQR of progression duration time. The first dataset will be used to fit a scaled Erlang distribution, which will then be re-scaled to actual time using overall mean.

# Obtain ccdf of PCR positivity
q <- seq(0, 100, l = 21)
df.edata <- data.frame(x = fit.edata$surv,y = fit.edata$cumhaz, z = fit.edata$time)
ccdf_pcr <- data.frame()
for (i in 1:21) {
  x = q[i+1]
  ccdf_pcr[1,i] <- df.edata$y[x]
}
ccdf_pcr <- cbind(0,ccdf_pcr)
ccdf_pcr <- ccdf_pcr[,1:21]
rownames(ccdf_pcr) <- "pcr positive"

# obtain mean, median and IQR of progression durations
progression_durations <- data.frame(param = "m_Com",
                                    Q2.5 = mean(df.edata$z[2],df.edata$z[3]),
                                    Q50 = df.edata$z[50],
                                    Q97.5 = mean(df.edata$z[97],df.edata$z[98]),
                                    mean = mean(df.edata$z))

# pass parameters on to Lilith's functions
source("fit_Erlang.R") ## this is kept offline

# Print outputs
